MENINGITIS, BACTERIAL - COTE D'IVOIRE: STREPTOCOCCUS PNEUMONIAE ST.1 PREDOMINATES
**********************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 14 Mar 2016
From: Clarisse Kouame Elogne <nzolecla@yahoo.fr> [edited]


Pneumococcal infection in the Meningitis Outbreak of 2016 in West Africa: Cote d'Ivoire
-------------------
Bacterial meningitis is an infection caused by 3 main germs named _Neisseria meningitidis_, _Haemophilus influenzae_ and _Streptococcus pneumoniae_. In Africa, meningitis causes each year sporadic cases in many countries and outbreaks in countries along the meningitis belt in West and Central Africa. In 2012, _Neisseria meningitidis_ was the cause of the epidemic with a predominant serogroup NmW135 in Cote d'Ivoire. In 2016 _Streptococcus pneumoniae_ was confirmed to be the main agent of the meningitis epidemic in Ghana. This article aims to bring forward the features of the circulating serotypes of this epidemic that caused 50% mortality in order to contribute to the therapeutic and immunization response to the serotypes components of vaccines.

A total of 66 cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) were collected from the National Reference Center of Meningitis in Pasteur Institute of Cote d'Ivoire, which were coming from areas affected by the epidemic germs. The identification of the germs was made through conventional bacteriology and by the PCR method. The MIC (minimum inhibitory concentration) [was determined for] penicillin G and ceftriaxone. The _S. pneumoniae_ serotypes [were determined] by region based on differences in the [capsular] polyssacharides. The molecular serotyping of pneumococci was done according to the Rekha et al, 2006 Protocol.

Out of the 66 CSF collected from the patients suspected to have meningitis, 28 were positive with a rate of 42.4%: 71.4% (20/28) [were positive for] _S. pneumoniae_, 17.8% (5/28) [for] _N. meningitidis_ and 7.1% (2/28) _H. influenzae_ b.

The MIC [for an isolate of _S. pneumoniae_] was 0.015 to penicillin G and 0.06 mg/L for the ceftriaxone. The strains were very sensitive, allowing treatment according to the national protocol.

Serotyping (PCR) of _S. pneumoniae_ shows a distribution of 50% (10/20) for serotype 1, 5% (1/20) for serotype 12 and 5% (1/20) for the serotype 5.

These results confirm the predominance of serotype 1 _S. pneumoniae_ in Cote d'Ivoire. This is a polyclonal epidemic. The [molecular?] sequencing will clarify the characteristics of the serotype 1 strains.

--
Dr. Clarisse Kouame Elogne
Attaché de recherche
Unite de Bacteriologie Clinique
Responsable qualité et biosécurité
Institut Pasteur de CI
Cote d'Ivoire
