[ProMED-mail thanks Dr. Clarisse Kouame Elogne for submission of data on the etiology of bacterial meningitis in Cote d'Ivoire, a country in the African meningitis belt.

The usual pathogen in this region has been _Neisseria meningitidis_. However, several other bacterial species, including _Streptococcus pneumoniae_ and _Hemophilus pneumoniae_, have noted to be involved in bacterial meningitis outbreaks in the African meningitis belt before (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1699486).

Some studies have emphasized that _Streptococcus pneumoniae_ may cause outbreaks of bacterial meningitis in an epidemic pattern in the African meningitis belt during the dry season, especially in older children and young adults (http://jid.oxfordjournals.org/content/192/2/192.abstract?ijkey=9d47813b96aa1d50880f62e9e7efbc4d32bfea9a&keytype2=tf_ipsecsha and http://cid.oxfordjournals.org/content/43/6/693.abstract?ijkey=7d2ca30004fffc8d1410102f6ec758a72efc1f82&keytype2=tf_ipsecsha). _S. pneumoniae_ serotype 1 from a single clonal complex (ST 217) has predominated in several outbreaks, but other pneumococcal serotypes are also isolated. The case-fatality rate for pneumococcal meningitis has been high; over 40 percent of cases are fatal, regardless of age group.

Identifying the specific microbial causes of a bacterial meningitis outbreak is critically important, because prior meningococcal immunization programs with a particular serogroup vaccine in the region may have resulted in replacement of a previous serogroup with other meningococcal serogroups or the outbreak may actually be due to non-meningococcal bacterial species.

Use of a pneumococcal conjugate vaccine could be beneficial in an outbreak where pneumococcal etiology predominates. Pneumococcal conjugate vaccines reduce carriage of serotypes of _S. pneumoniae_ contained in the vaccine and thus person-to-person transmission of these pathogens, which occurs by close contact with respiratory secretions or saliva. However, the 7-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine was found to include serotypes (4, 6B, 9V, 14, 18C, 19F, and 23F) protective against only 8 percent of the isolates in one study in Burkina Faso (http://cid.oxfordjournals.org/content/43/6/693.full). The 13-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine, Prevnar 13, which covers serotypes 1, 3, 4, 5, 6A, 6B, 7F, 9V, 14, 18C, 19A, 19F, and 23F, may be more effective, especially when serotype 1 predominates. - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4095606,52.]
